@node Main "HDToolBox Patch for Optical Drives"

@{line}@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}HDToolBox Patch for Optical Drives@{ub} @{"1.1" link Version_History} (22-Feb-99)@{uu}
@{line}This document is copyright © 1999 by @{"Mark Knibbs" link Contacting}@{par}@{jleft}

This document is freely distributable for non-commercial purposes. Inclusion
with a commercial product (including shareware) is permissable only if I am
sent a copy of the product.@{par}

HDToolBox is Commodore's utility for partitioning and formatting SCSI storage
devices such as hard disks. It is supplied on the AmigaOS Install disk.@{par}

HDToolBox cannot be properly used with SCSI devices that are set to "optical
memory device" mode, as opposed to "direct access device", which is normal for
hard disks. This applies to magneto-optical drives and Panasonic's PD
rewriteable drive. It may also apply to DVD-RAM drives. For more information
on magneto-optical drives, see my Amiga Magneto-Optical Drive FAQ, on Aminet as
@{fg shine}docs/help/Amiga_MO_FAQ.lha@{fg text}.@{par}

HDToolBox checks the device type, and if non-zero refuses to read data from the
drive. Type 0 is direct access, type 7 is optical memory. This is not a major
problem as MO drives typically have a DIP switch to set the device type to
either 0 or 7. Nevertheless, it would be nice to use HDToolBox with optical
drives in optical memory device mode.@{par}

That is what the following patch allows. It modifies HDToolBox to work with
both devices of type 0 and type 7. Luckily, because HDToolBox is written in C,
there were just enough spare instructions so that I didn't have to alter the
program size.@{par}

I have created patches for five versions of HDToolBox:
@{lindent 4}@{pari -2}@{par}· Version 2.2 is on the "Amiga Developer CD v1.1"@{par}
· Version 2.22 is on the AmigaOS 2.05 Install disk@{par}
· Version 39.12 is on the AmigaOS 3.0 Install disk@{par}
· Version 40.3 is on the AmigaOS 40.35 (beta 3.1) Install disk@{par}
· Version 40.4 is on the AmigaOS 3.1 Install disk@{pard}@{par}

If you have another version of HDToolBox, please @{"contact me" link Contacting}.@{par}

Use a binary file editor such as Hex (on Aminet,
@{fg shine}disk/moni/HexED.lha@{fg text}) to make the changes to the HDToolBox
executable. All numbers are in hexadecimal.@{par}

@{b}HDToolBox 2.2 and 2.22 patch@{par}
@{code}@{jcenter}@{u}Offset     Change From        Change To     @{uu}
$004602@{ub}    102D FEF7 4A00     7000 102D FEF7
@{b}$00460A@{ub}    7200 1200 2001     0C00 0007 6712@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

@{b}HDToolBox 39.12 patch@{par}
@{code}@{jcenter}@{u}Offset     Change From        Change To     @{uu}
$0042A6@{ub}    102D FEF7 4A00     7000 102D FEF7
@{b}$0042AE@{ub}    7200 1200 2001     0C00 0007 6712@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

@{b}HDToolBox 40.3 patch@{par}
@{code}@{jcenter}@{u}Offset     Change From        Change To     @{uu}
$005444@{ub}    102D FEF7 4A00     7000 102D FEF7
@{b}$00544C@{ub}    7200 1200 2001     0C00 0007 6712@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

@{b}HDToolBox 40.4 patch@{par}
@{code}@{jcenter}@{u}Offset     Change From        Change To     @{uu}
$005430@{ub}    102D FEF7 4A00     7000 102D FEF7
@{b}$005438@{ub}    7200 1200 2001     0C00 0007 6712@{par}@{jleft}@{body}

Alternatively, I have created patch files for use in conjunction with GPatch
(on Aminet, @{fg shine}util/misc/gpatch.lha@{fg text}). You can use these to
patch your HDToolBox executable if you prefer not to apply the patch manually.
The filenames are @{b}HDToolBox2.2_MO.gpch@{ub},
@{b}HDToolBox2.22_MO.gpch@{ub}, @{b}HDToolBox39.12_MO.gpch@{ub},
@{b}HDToolBox40.3_MO.gpch@{ub} and @{b}HDToolBox40.4_MO.gpch@{ub} for versions
2.2, 2.22, 39.12, 40.3 and 40.4 respectively.@{par}

For example, to use GPatch to patch your HDToolBox 40.4 executable you would
use commands like:@{code}
@{jcenter}Rename HDToolBox HDToolBox.orig                      
GPatch HDToolBox.orig HDToolBox40.4_MO.gpch HDToolBox@{par}@{jleft}

@endnode


